(verb
  :name "math/digit-at"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/digit-at n place) -> number"
  :summary "Extracts the digit of n at the 10^place position."
  :explanation "Returns a single digit from a number by place-value position. The place parameter indexes powers of 10: place=0 is the ones, place=1 is the tens, place=2 is the hundreds, and so on. This verb makes place-value decomposition explicit and visible, fundamental to understanding decimal structure. Use it to teach why 253 has a 5 in the tens place, or to build place-value visualization tools."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/digit-at 253 1)" :note "Returns 5—the tens digit of 253")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (number-to-digits n)\n  (let ((places (math/count-on 0 4)))\n    (map (lambda (p) (math/digit-at n p)) places)))" :note "Decompose a number into its four rightmost digits (ones, tens, hundreds, thousands)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (expand-place-value n)\n  (let ((digits (map (lambda (p) (math/digit-at n p))\n                     (math/count-on 0 5))))\n    (map * digits (map (lambda (p) (math/pow 10 p))\n                       (math/count-on 0 5)))))" :note "Reconstruct expanded form: each digit multiplied by its place value (200 50 3 ...)")
  )
  :caveats ("place=0 is the ones position; place=1 is tens; place=2 is hundreds. This is standard but worth stating clearly." "Asking for a place beyond the number's magnitude returns 0 (e.g., digit-at 25 3 returns 0)" "Negative numbers: digit-at extracts from the absolute value; the sign is discarded")
  :drawbacks ("Extracts one digit at a time; for full decomposition, compose with math/count-on and map" "Only meaningful for integers; for floats, results depend on truncation—use with care")
  :usecases ("Teaching place-value understanding in elementary numeracy" "Building place-value visualization tools (place-value charts, base-10 blocks)" "Decomposing numbers for regrouping lessons in addition/subtraction")
  :related ("math/expanded-form" "math/place-value" "math/count-on")
  :learn (:concept "Positional notation (place value) made explicit and queryable" :prerequisites ("core forms: map, lambda, math/count-on, math/pow") :progression "Pair with math/expanded-form to see the full decomposition; use in area-model and regrouping lessons")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A tutor asks a student for the tens digit of 253; the operator needs to extract it programmatically to compare." :program "(define (tens-digit n) (math/digit-at n 1))
(tens-digit 253)" :explanation "Extract by place index." :meta "math/digit-at is the correct verb because it names the place-value operation. Modulo/division works but hides intent.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: positional index — extract a component by its place."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/digit-at 253 1)")
       (:domain "phone number (a metaphor domain — the fourth digit of a phone number)" :code "(define (nth-digit num k) (list num k))")
       (:domain "math — kth coefficient of a polynomial in base b" :code "(define (coef n k b) (list n k b))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung selects a positional component from a compound value."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'get element at position' is universal.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Reassembling every digit at its place returns the original number." :program "(define n 253)
(define d0 (math/digit-at n 0))
(define d1 (math/digit-at n 1))
(define d2 (math/digit-at n 2))
(= n (+ (* d2 100) (* d1 10) d0))" :invariant "∀ n ∈ ℕ. n = Σ digit-at(n, k) · 10^k" :meta "Positional-notation identity. If broken, the digit extractor is off. See book-of-math ch 3 (place value).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain digit-at with map to decompose a number." :composition "(define (decompose n)
  (map (lambda (p) (math/digit-at n p)) (math/count-on 0 4)))
(decompose 4028)" :emergent "extractor-over-positions: pointwise application across a place range." :meta "Belongs to the family of positional-decomposition patterns. See book-of-composition ch 7.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/exp"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/exp x) -> number"
  :summary "Returns e^x, where e is Euler's number (≈ 2.71828)."
  :explanation "Computes the exponential function, raising e to the power x. This is a transcendental function fundamental to growth models, calculus, and probability. The result is always positive and increases exponentially. Use math/exp when modeling compound growth, radioactive decay, or populations. Pair it with log for the inverse relationship."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/exp 0)" :note "Returns 1 (e^0 = 1, always true)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (bacteria-count initial-pop time)\n  (* initial-pop (math/exp time)))" :note "Model exponential population growth with per-unit-time rate = 1")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (radioactive-decay initial-mass half-life elapsed-time)\n  (let ((decay-constant (/ (log 2) half-life)))\n    (* initial-mass (math/exp (- (* decay-constant elapsed-time))))))" :note "Compute remaining mass after radioactive decay using the decay constant from half-life")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns inexact floating-point; for large x, results may overflow to infinity" "Negative x gives small positive values; (math/exp -1) ≈ 0.368" "Composed inverse of math/log: (log (math/exp x)) ≈ x, up to floating-point precision")
  :drawbacks ("Very large arguments overflow; use for |x| < 700 or so" "Floating-point imprecision at extreme values; for exact symbolic work, use sym/exp or const/e")
  :usecases ("Modeling exponential growth (populations, investment compounds, epidemiology)" "Physics and chemistry (radioactive decay, reaction rates)" "Machine learning and statistics (softmax, log-likelihood)")
  :related ("math/log" "math/log-base" "math/pow" "const/e")
  :learn (:concept "The exponential function as the inverse of the natural logarithm" :prerequisites ("const/e" "math/log") :progression "Learn log next to understand the inverse; then explore exponential models in science")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "An operator models bacterial growth: initial population of 1000, growth rate 0.02 per hour, need count at t=5." :program "(define (grow n0 rate t) (* n0 (math/exp (* rate t))))
(grow 1000 0.02 5)" :explanation "Apply e^(rate·t) then scale by initial count." :meta "math/exp is the correct verb because exp captures continuous exponential growth. math/pow(e, x) would work but math/exp is direct and canonical.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: continuous exponentiation."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/exp 1)")
       (:domain "compound interest (a metaphor domain — continuous compounding)" :code "(define (comp p r t) (list p r t))")
       (:domain "math — e^x as the unique solution to y' = y" :code "(define (exp-of x) (list x))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung raises Euler's number to a real exponent."
     :meta "The shape transfers because e^x is the fundamental solution to exponential-growth ODEs.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "exp(a+b) = exp(a) · exp(b)." :program "(< (abs (- (math/exp (+ 1 2)) (* (math/exp 1) (math/exp 2)))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ a b ∈ ℝ. exp(a+b) = exp(a)·exp(b)" :meta "Group homomorphism (additive → multiplicative). If broken, the impl is not truly exp. See book-of-math ch 9 (exponential and log).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain exp with a decay constant for radioactive-decay half-life." :composition "(define (remain m0 half t)
  (let ((k (/ (log 2) half)))
    (* m0 (math/exp (- (* k t))))))
(remain 100 5 10)" :emergent "physics-decay: k drives an exponential fall-off." :meta "Belongs to the family of exponential-decay models. See book-of-composition ch 11.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/expanded-form"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/expanded-form n) -> list"
  :summary "Decomposes a number into its place-value components, returning a list of addends."
  :explanation "Breaks down a number into a sum of place-value terms. For example, 253 becomes (200 50 3). This representation makes the structure of decimal notation explicit and tangible. It is central to teaching how numbers are built from powers of 10, and serves as a bridge to algebraic thinking (polynomial decomposition). Use expanded-form when teaching regrouping, addition strategies, or multiplication."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/expanded-form 253)" :note "Returns (200 50 3)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (sum-expanded n)\n  (apply + (math/expanded-form n)))" :note "Verify that expanded form sums back to the original number")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (partial-products a b)\n  (let ((exp-a (math/expanded-form a))\n        (exp-b (math/expanded-form b)))\n    (map (lambda (x) (map (lambda (y) (* x y)) exp-b)) exp-a)))" :note "Generate the partial products for 2-digit multiplication by expanding both factors")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns only non-zero terms; (math/expanded-form 205) returns (200 5), omitting the zero tens" "Negative numbers: expanded-form applies to the absolute value; the sign is attached to the result" "Works best for integers; behavior on floats depends on truncation")
  :drawbacks ("Does not return a fixed-width representation; leading/trailing zeros are omitted" "For visualization, pair with math/area-model or math/fraction-bar for pedagogy-specific formats")
  :usecases ("Teaching place-value decomposition in elementary arithmetic" "Building multiplication and division strategies (area model, partial products)" "Scaffolding number sense and mental-math strategies")
  :related ("math/digit-at" "math/area-model" "math/place-value" "math/count-on")
  :learn (:concept "Positional notation made additive and compositional" :prerequisites ("math/digit-at" "math/count-on" "core forms: map, apply, +") :progression "Use to understand math/area-model and partial-products strategies; then apply to algebraic polynomial expansion")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A tutor needs to decompose 253 as 200+50+3 for a place-value lesson." :program "(define (place-parts n) (math/expanded-form n))
(place-parts 253)" :explanation "Return the list of nonzero place terms." :meta "math/expanded-form is the correct verb because it emits the decomposition. Extracting digits and multiplying by places by hand works but rewrites the pedagogy.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: decomposition — a whole broken into named parts."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/expanded-form 253)")
       (:domain "bill (a metaphor domain — total broken into subtotals per category)" :code "(define (bill parts) (list 'parts parts))")
       (:domain "math — n = Σ dk·10^k" :code "(define (place-poly digits) (list digits))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung breaks a value into a sum of place-labeled components."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'decomposition into a basis' is universal.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Summing the expanded form returns the original number." :program "(= 253 (apply + (math/expanded-form 253)))" :invariant "∀ n ∈ ℕ. Σ expanded-form(n) = n" :meta "Reconstruction identity. If broken, decomposition is lossy. See book-of-math ch 3.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain expanded-form with area-model for partial products in a lesson." :composition "(define (product-parts a b)
  (let ((ea (math/expanded-form a))
        (eb (math/expanded-form b)))
    (list 'parts (list ea eb))))
(product-parts 23 45)" :emergent "decompose-then-recombine: expansion drives a multiplication pipeline." :meta "Belongs to the family of place-value pedagogical composers. See book-of-composition ch 15.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/fraction-bar"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/fraction-bar num den shaded) -> spec"
  :summary "Generates a visual fraction-bar specification with numerator, denominator, and shaded count."
  :explanation "Creates a model of a fraction as a bar divided into equal parts, with some shaded. This is a fundamental visual tool for teaching fractional reasoning: it makes the relationship between parts and wholes transparent. A fraction 3/5 is visualized as a bar split into 5 equal regions, with 3 colored. Use this when introducing fractions, comparing fractions, or teaching addition of fractions with like denominators."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/fraction-bar 3 5 3)" :note "Bar with 5 parts, all 3 shaded; represents the fraction 3/5")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (compare-fractions n1 d1 n2 d2)\n  (list (math/fraction-bar n1 d1 n1)\n        (math/fraction-bar n2 d2 n2)))" :note "Display two fractions side by side for visual comparison")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (add-fractions-like-denom n1 d n2)\n  (let ((result-shaded (+ n1 n2)))\n    (if (> result-shaded d)\n      (list (math/fraction-bar d d d)\n            (math/fraction-bar (- result-shaded d) d (- result-shaded d)))\n      (math/fraction-bar result-shaded d result-shaded))))" :note "Add two fractions with the same denominator, showing overflow as a whole plus remainder")
  )
  :caveats ("shaded must not exceed den (denominator); values > den may be rendered as overflow or error" "The spec is symbolic/structural; actual rendering is done by downstream visualization" "num (numerator) is distinct from shaded count in some contexts; clarify which part of the spec is which")
  :drawbacks ("Fraction bars are one visual model; does not generate other models (area, length line, set model)" "Best for fractions < 1 or simple improper fractions; large denominators may render poorly")
  :usecases ("Teaching fraction concepts and part-whole relationships" "Comparing fractions visually (which is larger?)" "Adding and subtracting fractions with like denominators")
  :related ("math/ratio-bar" "math/area-model" "math/integer-line")
  :learn (:concept "Visual representation of rational numbers as part-to-whole ratios" :prerequisites ("core forms: list") :progression "After fraction bars, explore math/ratio-bar for ratio thinking; then move to symbolic fraction operations")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A lesson introduces 3/5 with a bar divided into 5 parts, 3 shaded." :program "(define spec (math/fraction-bar 3 5 3))
spec" :explanation "Emit the spec for a rendering system." :meta "math/fraction-bar is the correct verb because it names the pedagogy. A generic rectangle spec would work but loses the fraction semantics.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: part-of-whole visualization."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/fraction-bar 3 5 3)")
       (:domain "pie chart (a metaphor domain — slice size shows fraction of total)" :code "(define (pie parts) (list parts)))")
       (:domain "math — rational number as a pair (numerator, denominator)" :code "(define (frac n d) (list n d))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung shows a fraction as a visual share."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'part-of-whole' is a universal representation.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "The shaded count must not exceed the denominator." :program "(<= 3 5)" :invariant "∀ shaded, denominator ∈ ℕ. shaded ≤ denominator (for a proper visualization)" :meta "Proper-fraction invariant. If broken, the spec renders incorrectly. See book-of-math ch 6 (fractions).")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain fraction-bar with a comparison view." :composition "(define (compare-frac n1 d1 n2 d2)
  (list (math/fraction-bar n1 d1 n1) (math/fraction-bar n2 d2 n2)))
(compare-frac 3 5 2 3)" :emergent "side-by-side comparison of two fractional shares." :meta "Belongs to the family of parallel-view patterns. See book-of-composition ch 15.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/integer-line"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/integer-line min max) -> spec"
  :summary "Generates a number-line specification spanning from min to max, including both positive and negative integers."
  :explanation "Creates a visual integer number line model that stretches across negative and positive territory, making the structure of the integers and their relationships transparent. This verb is central to teaching directed number, signed arithmetic, and inequality. Unlike a simple counting sequence, a number line situates each number in a continuous spatial context and reveals distance, direction, and ordering simultaneously."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/integer-line -5 5)" :note "Line spanning from -5 to 5, centered at origin; shows symmetry of negatives")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (show-number-and-opposite n)\n  (math/integer-line (- n) n))" :note "Display a number and its additive inverse on the same line")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (distance-on-line a b)\n  (let ((line (math/integer-line (min a b) (max a b))))\n    (- (max a b) (min a b))))" :note "Visualize distance as the span of the line segment between two integers")
  )
  :caveats ("min and max should be integers; behavior on floats depends on truncation or rounding" "Large ranges (e.g., -1000 to 1000) may produce unwieldy specs; for visualization, mark only strategic points" "The spec is symbolic; actual rendering handles tick-mark density and label placement")
  :drawbacks ("Covers integers only; for dense representations (decimals, rationals), use a number-line with different semantics" "Long number lines with many marks become cluttered; pair with zoom/focus for big ranges")
  :usecases ("Teaching integer ordering and comparison across zero" "Modeling addition and subtraction as movement along the line" "Visualizing inequality and distance concepts")
  :related ("math/number-line" "math/compare" "math/digit-at")
  :learn (:concept "The number line as a spatial model of integer structure and order" :prerequisites ("math/count-on") :progression "After integer line, extend to number-line for continuous values; use in signed arithmetic and inequality lessons")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A signed-arithmetic lesson needs a number line from -5 to 5." :program "(define spec (math/integer-line -5 5))
spec" :explanation "Emit the spec with tick marks at integers." :meta "math/integer-line is the correct verb because it covers negatives and zero explicitly. number-line is a superset but integer-line makes the integer-tick pedagogy explicit.")
