(verb
  :name "math/log"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(log x) -> number"
  :summary "Returns ln(x), the natural logarithm of x (base e). Escalates if x ≤ 0."
  :explanation "Computes the natural logarithm, the inverse of math/exp. Given a positive number x, log returns the power to which e must be raised to get x. This function is fundamental to calculus, exponential models, and probability. The domain is strictly positive (x > 0); any attempt to log zero or negative numbers triggers an escalation (an error signal in Motoi Scheme). Pair with math/exp for inverse relationships, or with math/log-base to change the base."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(log 1)" :note "Returns 0 (e^0 = 1, so ln(1) = 0)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (exponential-time-to-target initial-pop target-pop)\n  (/ (log (/ target-pop initial-pop)) 1))" :note "Solve for time in exponential growth: ln(target/initial) = time × growth-rate")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (half-life-from-decay-constant k)\n  (/ (log 2) k))" :note "Relate the decay constant k to physical half-life: t_half = ln(2) / k")
  )
  :caveats ("Domain is x > 0 only; zero and negative inputs escalate (error signal)" "log returns inexact float; for symbolic work or exact values, use sym/log or const/ln2" "Inverse relationship: (math/exp (log x)) ≈ x, up to floating-point precision")
  :drawbacks ("No simple closed form for logarithms of arbitrary rational numbers" "Floating-point errors accumulate with repeated log operations; be cautious in numerical chains")
  :usecases ("Solving exponential equations (finding time, rate, or scaling factor)" "Modeling logarithmic scales (pH, decibels, Richter scale, stock market returns)" "Information theory and probability (entropy, log-likelihood)")
  :related ("math/exp" "math/log-base" "math/log10" "math/log2" "const/e" "const/ln2" "const/ln10")
  :learn (:concept "Logarithm as the inverse of exponential growth, and as a tool for solving equations" :prerequisites ("math/exp" "const/e") :progression "Master log and exp as inverses; then learn math/log-base to work with other bases; apply to exponential models and scale transformations")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "An operator solves for time in an exponential-decay model: given decay constant k, target mass fraction m/m0, find t." :program "(define (decay-time k frac) (/ (- (log frac)) k))
(decay-time 0.1 0.5)" :explanation "Apply log to the mass fraction, negate, divide by k." :meta "log (natural log) is the correct verb because the model uses e as base. log-base with e would work but log is direct.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: inverse of exponential."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(log 2.71828)")
       (:domain "piano keys (a metaphor domain — doubling frequency = one octave; log tells you how many octaves)" :code "(define (octaves f0 f) (list f0 f)))")
       (:domain "math — inverse of exp; e^(log x) = x" :code "(define (inv-exp x) (list x))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung inverts a continuous exponential growth to recover the exponent."
     :meta "The shape transfers because logarithm is the group inverse of exp on the positive reals.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "log(a·b) = log(a) + log(b)." :program "(< (abs (- (log 6) (+ (log 2) (log 3)))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ a b > 0. log(a·b) = log(a) + log(b)" :meta "Group homomorphism (multiplicative → additive). If broken, the impl is not truly log. See book-of-math ch 9.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain log with subtraction for a ratio." :composition "(define (log-ratio a b) (- (log a) (log b)))
(log-ratio 100 10)" :emergent "difference-of-logs = log-of-ratio." :meta "Belongs to the family of homomorphism-under-difference patterns. See book-of-composition ch 11.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/log-base"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/log-base b x) -> number"
  :summary "Computes the logarithm of x in base b."
  :explanation "Logarithm answers: 'b to what power equals x?' The result is the exponent. For instance, log base 2 of 8 is 3 because 2³ = 8. This verb accepts any positive base b (except 1) and any positive x; the result is a real number that may be fractional. Internally it uses the change-of-base formula: log_b(x) = ln(x) / ln(b). Returns inexact floating-point values."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/log-base 2 8)" :note "Returns 3 because 2³ = 8; the simplest logarithmic query.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((result (math/log-base 10 1000)))\n  (list 'log10-of-1000 result))" :note "Base 10 logarithm; log₁₀(1000) = 3. Shows binding and composition.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (solve-exponential base target)\n  (math/log-base base target))\n(solve-exponential const/e 7.389)" :note "Wrapping in a helper that solves b^x = target by returning log_b(target). Demonstrates the verb's role in inverse problems.")
  )
  :caveats ("Base must be positive and not equal to 1." "Argument x must be positive; x ≤ 0 will produce a non-real or undefined result." "Results are inexact floating-point; use for numerical approximation, not exact symbolic work." "log_b(1) always returns 0 for any valid base b.")
  :drawbacks ("Floating-point precision limits precision for very large or very small arguments." "Cannot be used for symbolic or exact rational arithmetic; see sym/* for symbolic work." "Slower than math/log2 or math/log10 if those special cases apply.")
  :usecases ("Solving exponential equations: if b^x = y, then x = log_b(y)." "Converting between logarithm bases during analysis or calculation." "Measuring information gain or entropy in non-standard bases." "Modeling growth rates or decay with arbitrary scaling.")
  :related ("math/log10" "math/log2" "math/pow" "math/exp" "math/log" "const/e" "const/ln2" "const/ln10")
  :learn (:concept "Logarithm as the inverse of exponentiation: if b^x = y, then x = log_b(y)." :prerequisites ("math/pow" "const/e") :progression "After mastering math/log-base, explore log (natural log) and the constants const/e, const/ln2, const/ln10 for deeper understanding of logarithmic scales.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A CS teacher shows students that log₂(8) = 3." :program "(define (log2-of n) (math/log-base 2 n))
(log2-of 8)" :explanation "Apply the closed form log_b(x) = ln(x)/ln(b)." :meta "math/log-base is the correct verb when the base is not e, 10, or 2. For those, use log, math/log10, math/log2.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: base-parametrized inverse of exponentiation."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/log-base 2 8)")
       (:domain "half-lives (a metaphor domain — how many halvings to reach target?)" :code "(define (halvings from to) (list from to))")
       (:domain "math — change of base log_b(x) = ln(x)/ln(b)" :code "(define (cob b x) (list b x)))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung finds an exponent given a base and a target."
     :meta "The shape transfers because logarithms in any base measure a group action.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "log_b(b) = 1." :program "(< (abs (- (math/log-base 2 2) 1)) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ b > 0, b ≠ 1. log-base(b, b) = 1" :meta "Self-log identity. If broken, the change-of-base ratio is wrong. See book-of-math ch 9.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain log-base with a comparison for algorithm-complexity." :composition "(define (complexity-ratio n)
  (list 'n2 (* n n) 'nlogn (* n (math/log-base 2 n))))
(complexity-ratio 1024)" :emergent "complexity-model: log-base drives an asymptotic estimate." :meta "Belongs to the family of algorithmic-complexity comparisons. See book-of-code ch 11.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/log10"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/log10 x) -> number"
  :summary "Computes the logarithm of x in base 10."
  :explanation "Logarithm base 10 is the inverse of 10^x. It answers 'what power of 10 gives me x?' This is the common logarithm, historically used in scientific tables and still natural for decimal-system reasoning. For example, log₁₀(100) = 2 because 10² = 100. Returns inexact floating-point values. Faster than the general math/log-base when base 10 is needed."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/log10 100)" :note "Returns 2; 10² = 100. The simplest case: exact powers of 10.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (ph-from-h-plus concentration)\n  (- (math/log10 concentration)))\n(ph-from-h-plus 0.0001)" :note "pH is defined as −log₁₀[H⁺]. Shows a real-world use: chemistry.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (decibel-ratio power-ratio)\n  (* 10 (math/log10 power-ratio)))\n(let ((ratio 100))\n  (decibel-ratio ratio))" :note "Decibel is 10·log₁₀(ratio). Shows use in audio/signal processing.")
  )
  :caveats ("Argument must be positive; x ≤ 0 produces non-real or undefined result." "log₁₀(1) always returns 0." "log₁₀(10) always returns 1." "Results are inexact floating-point approximations.")
  :drawbacks ("Only useful when base 10 is semantically appropriate; for other bases, use math/log-base." "Floating-point precision limits accuracy for extreme values." "Not suitable for symbolic or exact rational computation.")
  :usecases ("Computing pH in chemistry (pH = −log₁₀[H⁺])." "Calculating decibel levels in audio and signal processing." "Measuring orders of magnitude in scientific notation." "Converting between linear and logarithmic scales in data visualization.")
  :related ("math/log-base" "math/log2" "math/pow" "math/log" "const/ln10")
  :learn (:concept "Base 10 logarithm: the inverse of powers of 10, natural for decimal reasoning." :prerequisites ("math/pow") :progression "Learn math/log2 for computer science applications, then math/log-base for arbitrary bases, then log for natural logarithm.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A chemistry app computes pH from hydrogen-ion concentration." :program "(define (ph h+) (- (math/log10 h+)))
(ph 1e-4)" :explanation "Apply -log₁₀ to the concentration." :meta "math/log10 is the correct verb because pH is defined in base 10. Using math/log-base(10, ...) works but log10 is idiomatic.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape as log-base but fixed on base 10."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/log10 100)")
       (:domain "Richter scale (a metaphor domain — each unit = 10× amplitude)" :code "(define (richter amp) (list amp))")
       (:domain "math — decimal exponent recovery" :code "(define (dec-exp x) (list x)))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung finds the base-10 exponent of a positive number."
     :meta "The shape transfers because decibel, pH, and Richter are all base-10 logs.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "log10(10^n) = n." :program "(< (abs (- (math/log10 1000) 3)) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ n ∈ ℝ. log10(10^n) = n" :meta "Inverse of powers of 10. If broken, the base constant is wrong. See book-of-math ch 9.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain log10 into a decibel formula." :composition "(define (db ratio) (* 10 (math/log10 ratio)))
(db 100)" :emergent "science-scale: log10 drives a decibel/pH/Richter measure." :meta "Belongs to the family of logarithmic-scale measurements. See book-of-composition ch 11.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/log2"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/log2 x) -> number"
  :summary "Computes the logarithm of x in base 2."
  :explanation "Logarithm base 2 is the inverse of 2^x. It answers 'how many times do I double to reach x?' Essential in computer science, where data is binary. For example, log₂(8) = 3 because 2³ = 8. This counts the number of bits needed to represent x distinct values. Returns inexact floating-point values."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/log2 16)" :note "Returns 4; 2⁴ = 16. Counting doublings in powers of 2.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (bits-needed count)\n  (+ 1 (math/log2 count)))\n(bits-needed 256)" :note "Computing bit width needed to represent count distinct values; ⌈log₂(count)⌉ bits.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (fold-left f init xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc init))\n    (if (null? xs) acc (loop (cdr xs) (f acc (car xs))))))\n(define (information-entropy probabilities)\n  (fold-left (lambda (sum p)\n              (if (> p 0)\n                (- sum (* p (math/log2 p)))\n                sum))\n            0\n            probabilities))\n(information-entropy (list 0.5 0.25 0.25))" :note "Shannon entropy uses log₂ to measure information in bits per symbol.")
  )
  :caveats ("Argument must be positive; x ≤ 0 produces non-real or undefined result." "log₂(1) always returns 0." "log₂(2) always returns 1." "Results are inexact floating-point approximations.")
  :drawbacks ("Only useful in contexts where base 2 is semantically meaningful; otherwise use math/log-base." "Floating-point precision can degrade with extreme values." "Not suitable for exact symbolic arithmetic.")
  :usecases ("Computing information entropy and bit requirements in computer science." "Analyzing algorithm complexity and tree depth (binary search depth ≈ log₂ n)." "Determining the number of bits needed to encode a value." "Signal processing and Fourier analysis (FFT sizes are powers of 2).")
  :related ("math/log-base" "math/log10" "math/pow" "math/log" "const/ln2")
  :learn (:concept "Binary logarithm: inverse of powers of 2; fundamental to understanding computer representation." :prerequisites ("math/pow") :progression "After math/log2, explore math/log10 for scientific applications, then math/log-base for generalization, then log for natural logarithm and advanced calculus.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A CS course computes the number of bits needed to encode 256 distinct values." :program "(define (bits n) (math/log2 n))
(bits 256)" :explanation "Apply log₂ directly." :meta "math/log2 is the correct verb because it directly answers 'how many bits'. Using log-base with 2 works but log2 is idiomatic.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: base-2 exponent recovery."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/log2 256)")
       (:domain "tournament brackets (a metaphor domain — rounds to a single winner from n players)" :code "(define (rounds n) (list n)))")
       (:domain "math — bit-length of a power of 2" :code "(define (bitlen n) (list n))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung finds the base-2 exponent of a positive number."
     :meta "The shape transfers because base-2 is fundamental in CS and information theory.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "log2(2^n) = n." :program "(< (abs (- (math/log2 1024) 10)) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ n ∈ ℝ. log2(2^n) = n" :meta "Inverse of powers of 2. If broken, the base constant is wrong. See book-of-math ch 9.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain log2 into an entropy calculation." :composition "(define (h p) (- (* p (math/log2 p)) (* (- 1 p) (math/log2 (- 1 p)))))
(h 0.5)" :emergent "information-theory: log2 drives entropy in bits." :meta "Belongs to the family of information-theoretic aggregations. See book-of-ml ch 5.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/mixed-number"
  :library "math"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(math/mixed-number improper-fraction) -> (whole numerator denominator) | 'nan"
  :summary "Convert an improper fraction to a mixed number (whole part + reduced proper fraction)."
  :explanation "Takes an improper fraction (as a list (numerator denominator)) and returns a three-element list (whole numerator denominator) where numerator < denominator (a proper fraction). For example, 7/3 becomes (2 1 3) meaning 2 + 1/3. If the denominator is zero, returns 'nan. The result fractions are always in lowest terms (fully reduced). This is useful for displaying fractions in human-readable form and for middle-school algebra curricula."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/mixed-number (list 7 3))" :note "7/3 becomes (2 1 3), i.e. 2 and 1/3.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (display-fraction frac)\n  (let ((mixed (math/mixed-number frac)))\n    (if (equal? mixed 'nan)\n      (display \"undefined\")\n      (let ((w (list-ref mixed 0))\n            (n (list-ref mixed 1))\n            (d (list-ref mixed 2)))\n        (display (string-append (number->string w) \" and \" (number->string n) \"/\" (number->string d)))))))\n(display-fraction (list 11 4))" :note "Convert and format a mixed number for display.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (filter pred xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc '()))\n    (cond ((null? xs) (reverse acc))\n          ((pred (car xs)) (loop (cdr xs) (cons (car xs) acc)))\n          (else (loop (cdr xs) acc)))))\n(define (solve-fraction-word-problem results)\n  (let ((answers (map\n    (lambda (r)\n      (let ((mn (math/mixed-number r)))\n        (if (equal? mn 'nan)\n          'error\n          (list 'whole (list-ref mn 0) 'frac (list (list-ref mn 1) (list-ref mn 2))))))\n    results)))\n    (filter (lambda (a) (not (equal? a 'error))) answers)))\n(solve-fraction-word-problem (list (list 15 4) (list 22 5) (list 9 0)))" :note "Batch-convert improper fractions and filter out errors (den=0).")
  )
  :caveats ("Denominator must be non-zero; zero returns 'nan without error." "Numerator and denominator are assumed to be integers; behavior with floats is undefined." "Negative fractions are supported; sign is carried in the numerator." "The result is always fully reduced (GCD normalized).")
  :drawbacks ("Requires fraction input as (num den) list; no string parsing." "Inverse verb (mixed number back to improper fraction) is not provided; use arithmetic." "No formatting or display verb; you must build display logic yourself.")
  :usecases ("Displaying fractions in human-readable form in curricula or tutorials." "Converting computation results to mixed number format for answers." "Parsing and simplifying fraction arithmetic in symbolic math." "Building fraction-based games or educational software.")
  :related ("exact/float->rat" "math/round" "math/avg" "geom/slope")
  :learn (:concept "Fraction normalization: converting improper to mixed form and reducing to lowest terms." :prerequisites ("list" "quotient" "modulo") :progression "Learn math/mixed-number, then exact/float->rat for decimal-to-fraction conversion.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A student's answer is 7/3; a display layer must show '2 and 1/3'." :program "(define (to-mixed nd) (math/mixed-number nd))
(to-mixed '(7 3))" :explanation "Convert improper to mixed. Returns (2 1 3)." :meta "math/mixed-number is the correct verb because the desired output is a mixed-number form. Quotient/remainder alone would give the pieces but not the reduced-fraction guarantee.")
