(verb
  :name "math/number-line"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/number-line lo hi step) -> spec"
  :summary "Produces a specification for rendering a number line from lo to hi with marks at step intervals."
  :explanation "A number line is a visual teaching tool showing numbers as points on a line. This verb creates a metadata spec describing the line's bounds (lo and hi), the spacing of tick marks (step), and other rendering information. It is commonly used in elementary mathematics to teach ordering, comparison, and basic arithmetic. The spec can be passed to rendering or visualization verbs that build the actual display."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/number-line 0 10 1)" :note "A line from 0 to 10 with marks every 1 unit; shows the integers 0–10.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (make-number-line-for-range min-val max-val)\n  (let ((range (- max-val min-val)))\n    (math/number-line min-val max-val (max 1 (quotient range 10)))))\n(make-number-line-for-range 25 75)" :note "Auto-scaling step size based on range; approximately 10 marks across.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (compare-on-line a b)\n  (let ((line (math/number-line (min a b -5) (max a b 5) 1)))\n    (list 'line line 'a a 'b b 'relation\n          (cond ((< a b) '<) ((= a b) '=) (else '>)))))\n(compare-on-line 3 7)" :note "Using a number line spec as context for comparing two values; teaching aid.")
  )
  :caveats ("lo should be less than hi; if lo >= hi, behavior is undefined." "step should be positive; step <= 0 will not produce sensible marks." "This returns a spec object, not a rendered image; another verb must visualize it." "lo, hi, and step need not be integers, but fractional steps may yield dense or sparse marks.")
  :drawbacks ("Spec-only: does not directly render or display; requires a separate visualization step." "Large ranges with small steps produce many marks; may be visually cluttered." "No built-in handling of logarithmic or non-uniform scales; use for linear scales only.")
  :usecases ("Creating visual aids for teaching number ordering and comparison." "Building contexts for arithmetic and fraction problems." "Illustrating inequalities and solution sets on a line." "Supporting interactive math applications that show number positions.")
  :related ("math/integer-line" "math/count-on" "math/skip-count" "math/compare")
  :learn (:concept "Number line as a visual representation of number order and magnitude." :prerequisites ("math/compare") :progression "After math/number-line, explore math/integer-line for negative numbers, then math/count-on and math/skip-count for sequences.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A lesson needs a decimal number line from 0 to 1 with marks at 0.1 intervals." :program "(define spec (math/number-line 0 1 0.1))
spec" :explanation "Emit the spec with the given step." :meta "math/number-line is the correct verb for a continuous or non-integer range. integer-line only handles integers.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape as integer-line but continuous."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/number-line 0 1 0.1)")
       (:domain "ruler (a metaphor domain — millimeter marks on a 30-cm ruler)" :code "(define (ruler length step) (list length step))")
       (:domain "math — discretized ℝ with fixed step size" :code "(define (discretize lo hi step) (list lo hi step))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung places evenly-spaced marks on a line."
     :meta "The shape transfers because sampling a real interval is universal.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "Given lo, hi, step, the number of marks is (hi-lo)/step + 1." :program "(define expected (+ 1 (/ (- 1 0) 0.1)))
(> expected 10)" :invariant "∀ lo, hi, step with step > 0. num-marks = ⌊(hi-lo)/step⌋ + 1" :meta "Mark-count invariant. If broken, spec has wrong tick count. See book-of-math ch 8.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain number-line with map to place data markers." :composition "(define (mark-data data lo hi step)
  (list 'line (math/number-line lo hi step)
        'data data))
(mark-data '(0.2 0.5 0.8) 0 1 0.1)" :emergent "line-plus-data: axis and points together." :meta "Belongs to the family of visualization patterns. See book-of-composition ch 15.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/pct"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/pct n d) -> number"
  :summary "Compute n as a percentage of d; return 'nan if d is zero."
  :explanation "Percentage is a ratio scaled to 100. This verb divides n by d and multiplies by 100, giving you the fractional part of d that n represents. It is useful in tutorials, dashboards, and any context where you need to express one quantity as a share of a whole. When the denominator is zero, the result is the symbolic atom 'nan to signal undefined behavior without throwing."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/pct 25 100)" :note "Returns 25.0 — a quarter of a whole.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((score 87) (max-score 100))\n  (display (math/pct score max-score)))" :note "Bind variables from user input or state, then compute the percentage inline.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (grade-to-pct raw-marks total-marks)\n  (let ((pct (math/pct raw-marks total-marks)))\n    (cond ((equal? pct 'nan) 'error-div-by-zero)\n          ((>= pct 90) 'A)\n          ((>= pct 80) 'B)\n          (else 'C))))\n(grade-to-pct 78 100)" :note "Wrap math/pct in a decision tree; check for 'nan before branching on numeric ranges.")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns the symbolic atom 'nan (not a number), not a floating-point NaN; use equal? to test for it." "Division by zero returns 'nan silently; the verb does not escalate or throw." "Result is exact only for ratios that are exact; floating-point inputs yield floating-point results.")
  :drawbacks ("If you need percentages rounded to a fixed decimal place, compose with math/round afterward." "Does not validate that d is positive; negative denominators yield negative percentages.")
  :usecases ("Progress bars and completion meters (items-done / items-total)." "Grade-to-letter conversion and rubric thresholds." "Resource utilization (memory-used / memory-total)." "Survey or poll result aggregation (responses-for-choice / total-responses).")
  :related ("math/round" "math/avg" "math/sum")
  :learn (:concept "Percentages as scaled ratios; handling undefined division." :prerequisites ("(core)/divide" "(core)/number?") :progression "Once comfortable with math/pct, move to math/round to format percentages for display, then to math/avg and math/sum for aggregating multiple percentages.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A scoring dashboard needs to display raw/max as a percentage." :program "(define (as-pct raw max) (math/pct raw max))
(as-pct 87 100)" :explanation "Apply n/d × 100 with 'nan protection for d=0." :meta "math/pct is the correct verb because it handles div-by-zero and returns 'nan symbolically. Doing (* 100 (/ n d)) crashes on d=0.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: normalized-ratio."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/pct 25 100)")
       (:domain "battery level (a metaphor domain — current charge as % of full)" :code "(define (charge cur cap) (list cur cap))")
       (:domain "math — ratio scaled to [0, 100]" :code "(define (ratio-100 n d) (list n d))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung normalizes two values into a percentage."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'ratio to whole' is universal.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "pct(n, d) = 100 · (n/d) when d ≠ 0." :program "(< (abs (- (math/pct 25 100) 25)) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ n ∈ ℝ, d ≠ 0. pct(n, d) = 100·n/d" :meta "Closed-form pct identity. If broken, the coefficient 100 is missing. See book-of-math ch 6.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain pct with a threshold check." :composition "(define (pass? raw max threshold-pct)
  (let ((p (math/pct raw max)))
    (and (not (equal? p 'nan)) (>= p threshold-pct))))
(pass? 87 100 80)" :emergent "pct-plus-threshold: percentage gates a boolean." :meta "Belongs to the family of ratio-gated decisions. See book-of-composition ch 12.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/place-value"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/place-value n) -> a-list | 'nan"
  :summary "Decompose an integer into a list of (digit place) pairs; non-integers return 'nan."
  :explanation "Place-value decomposition breaks a whole number into its constituent digits and their place magnitudes (ones, tens, hundreds, etc.). The output is an association list where each pair is (digit place-exponent), e.g., 307 becomes ((3 2) (0 1) (7 0)). This is a curriculum verb designed to teach the structure of positional notation and to help with number sense. Non-integers and invalid inputs return 'nan."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/place-value 305)" :note "Returns ((3 2) (0 1) (5 0)), showing 3 hundreds, 0 tens, 5 ones.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (fold-left f init xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc init))\n    (if (null? xs) acc (loop (cdr xs) (f acc (car xs))))))\n(define (sum-of-place-values n)\n  (fold-left (lambda (acc pair) (+ acc (* (car pair) (expt 10 (cadr pair)))))\n            0\n            (math/place-value n)))\n(sum-of-place-values 142)" :note "Reconstruct the number by folding over the a-list; validates that decomposition is reversible.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (digit-at-place n place-exp)\n  (let ((decomp (math/place-value n)))\n    (cond ((equal? decomp 'nan) 'nan)\n          (else (let ((pair (assoc place-exp decomp)))\n                  (if pair (car pair) 0))))))\n(digit-at-place 4028 1)" :note "Look up a specific place in the decomposition using assoc; returns 0 if the place is absent (e.g., tens digit of 4028 is 2, not 0).")
  )
  :caveats ("Only accepts integers; 3.14 or any fractional input returns 'nan." "Includes leading zeros; 305 includes (0 1) for the absent tens place." "The a-list does not sort; order depends on digit traversal." "Negative integers: behavior is *[verify]* — confirm whether negation is dropped or preserved.")
  :drawbacks ("For teaching only; use math/pct or arithmetic for actual numeric work." "Inefficient for very large numbers (though Motoi integers are usually bounded)." "Does not handle scientific notation or other bases (binary, hexadecimal).")
  :usecases ("Elementary-school place-value lessons and base-10 understanding." "Building intuition for regrouping and carrying in addition/subtraction." "Digit-sum and digit-product problems (sum-of-digits, multiplication of place digits)." "Visualizing number structure in educational interfaces.")
  :related ("math/round-to-place" "math/mixed-number" "exact/float->rat")
  :learn (:concept "Positional notation and place-value decomposition." :prerequisites ("(core)/number?" "(core)/list" "(core)/assoc") :progression "After understanding place-value, learn math/round-to-place to see how place values guide rounding decisions, then move to exact/float->rat for rational representation.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A pedagogy tool needs to show the ones, tens, and hundreds of 305." :program "(define (decompose n) (math/place-value n))
(decompose 305)" :explanation "Return the association list ((3 2) (0 1) (5 0))." :meta "math/place-value is the correct verb because it emits the digit-place pair list. digit-at gives one digit at a time — this gives them all with places.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: full positional decomposition."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/place-value 305)")
       (:domain "time (a metaphor domain — 3h 5m 20s from 11120 seconds)" :code "(define (hms secs) (list secs))")
       (:domain "math — decomposition into basis vectors" :code "(define (in-basis n b) (list n b))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung breaks a compound value into positional pieces."
     :meta "The shape transfers because 'decompose into positional basis' is universal.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    :runs "spec-only"
   
    (:claim "Summing digit×10^place returns the original." :program "(define pv (math/place-value 305))
(define total (fold-left (lambda (acc pair) (+ acc (* (car pair) (expt 10 (cadr pair))))) 0 pv))
(= 305 total)" :invariant "∀ n ∈ ℕ. Σ pair-value(pv) = n where pv = place-value(n)" :meta "Reconstruction identity. If broken, decomposition is lossy. See book-of-math ch 3.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain place-value with a filter to find nonzero digits." :composition "(define (nonzero-places n)
  (filter (lambda (p) (not (zero? (car p)))) (math/place-value n)))
(nonzero-places 4028)" :emergent "decompose-and-filter." :meta "Belongs to the family of positional-decomposition patterns. See book-of-composition ch 7.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/pow"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/pow b e) -> number"
  :summary "Computes b raised to the power e (b^e)."
  :explanation "Exponentiation is repeated multiplication: b^e means b multiplied by itself e times (when e is a positive integer). More generally, it extends to negative exponents (b^(−e) = 1/b^e), fractional exponents (b^(1/n) = nth root of b), and real exponents (via logarithms). For example, 2^3 = 8 and 4^0.5 = 2. Returns inexact floating-point values. The base b should be positive for arbitrary real exponents."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/pow 2 3)" :note "Returns 8; 2³ = 2×2×2. Basic exponentiation.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (compound-interest principal rate years)\n  (* principal (math/pow (+ 1 rate) years)))\n(compound-interest 1000 0.05 10)" :note "Finance: A = P(1 + r)^t grows exponentially at rate r over t years.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (fold-left f init xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc init))\n    (if (null? xs) acc (loop (cdr xs) (f acc (car xs))))))\n(define (power-series x n-terms)\n  (fold-left (lambda (sum k)\n              (+ sum (/ (math/pow x k) (comb/factorial k))))\n            0\n            (list-copy (map (lambda (i) i) (list 0)))))\n(power-series 1 5)" :note "Building a power series (here sketched; e^x ≈ Σ x^k/k!). Shows composition with factorial.")
  )
  :caveats ("For negative base b and non-integer exponent e, result may be complex (not returned)." "Zero to a negative power (0^(−e)) is undefined; may escalate." "Exponent 0: b^0 = 1 for any nonzero b." "Results are inexact floating-point; precision degrades for very large or very small exponents." "1^e always returns 1 for any exponent e.")
  :drawbacks ("Floating-point precision limits; not suitable for exact symbolic work (use sym/pow)." "Cannot represent negative bases with fractional exponents." "Very large exponents can overflow to infinity; very small (negative large) exponents underflow to zero.")
  :usecases ("Modeling exponential growth (population, finance) and decay (half-life, radioactivity)." "Computing roots as fractional exponents (e.g., cube root as ^(1/3))." "Power series and polynomial evaluation." "Physics and engineering: velocity, acceleration, energy formulas.")
  :related ("math/log" "math/log-base" "math/log10" "math/log2" "math/exp" "const/e")
  :learn (:concept "Exponentiation as repeated multiplication, generalized to real exponents via logarithms." :prerequisites ("math/log") :progression "Master math/pow, then explore its inverse math/log-base, then apply both to growth/decay problems and financial modeling.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A financial model computes compound interest: A = P(1+r)^t." :program "(define (compound p r t) (* p (math/pow (+ 1 r) t)))
(compound 1000 0.05 10)" :explanation "Apply (1+r)^t and scale by principal." :meta "math/pow is the correct verb because the exponent can be any real. math/exp with log workaround is possible but less direct.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "Same shape: real exponentiation."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "math/*" :code "(math/pow 2 3)")
       (:domain "population (a metaphor domain — n doublings from an initial size)" :code "(define (pop-n n0 doublings) (list n0 doublings))")
       (:domain "math — b^e for b>0" :code "(define (power b e) (list b e))")
     )
     :explanation "Each rung raises a base to a real power."
     :meta "The shape transfers because b^e is fundamental to any scale-invariant process.")
    (:eng "Reuse of shape across substrates keeps the operator's mental model portable; the same debugging heuristics apply." :math "Cross-domain shape sharing is category-theoretic: the same universal property holds in every domain that satisfies the axioms." :cs "Cross-substrate reuse informs typeclass and trait design: the same shape becomes a shared interface across implementations."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "b^(a+c) = b^a · b^c." :program "(< (abs (- (math/pow 2 5) (* (math/pow 2 2) (math/pow 2 3)))) 1e-9)" :invariant "∀ b > 0, a c ∈ ℝ. b^(a+c) = b^a · b^c" :meta "Exponent-addition law. If broken, the impl is not exponentiation. See book-of-math ch 9.")
    (:eng "If the invariant fails at runtime, that is a fault log line — the pure algebra should hold; a break implies the impl regressed." :math "The invariant is the closed-form algebraic identity that defines the verb's essence; falsification by counterexample is what makes it engineering-grade math." :cs "The runnable check is a property test in the sense of QuickCheck; make it a smoke test in CI so regressions are caught before ship."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "Chain pow with a rate for a growth timeline." :composition "(define (grow-over n0 rate t) (* n0 (math/pow (+ 1 rate) t)))
(grow-over 100 0.1 5)" :emergent "growth-model: pow drives compound growth." :meta "Belongs to the family of exponential-growth models. See book-of-composition ch 11.")
    (:eng "Emergent patterns bring known operational discipline (retry, throttle, cache) into the verb chain; the operator inherits the pattern's diagnostics." :math "Composition preserves the algebraic properties of each verb; the emergent structure has its own (usually monoid) invariants worth naming." :cs "The named emergent (cache, throttle, sequencer, adapter, pipeline, projection) is the CS pattern-family label; reach for known-idiom debuggers when it appears.")))

(verb
  :name "math/ratio-bar"
  :library "math"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(math/ratio-bar a b) -> spec"
  :summary "Produces a specification for rendering a ratio bar visualizing the ratio a:b."
  :explanation "A ratio bar is a teaching model that visually represents the relationship between two quantities in a ratio a:b. The bar is divided into a units and b units (or segments proportional to a and b), helping students understand ratios as relationships between amounts. For example, a ratio 2:3 would show a bar divided into 5 equal parts, with 2 shaded on the left and 3 shaded (or unshaded) on the right. The verb returns a spec object suitable for rendering or visualization systems."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(math/ratio-bar 2 3)" :note "A ratio 2:3; spec describes a bar divided into 2 + 3 = 5 units.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(define (scale-ratio a b scale-factor)\n  (math/ratio-bar (* a scale-factor) (* b scale-factor)))\n(scale-ratio 1 4 5)" :note "Equivalent ratio: 1:4 scaled by 5 becomes 5:20. Demonstrates ratio equivalence.")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (ratio-problem girls boys)\n  (let ((spec (math/ratio-bar girls boys)))\n    (list 'ratio-spec spec\n          'total (+ girls boys)\n          'girl-fraction (/ girls (+ girls boys)))))\n(ratio-problem 8 12)" :note "Word-problem context: ratio bar used to find total and fractions.")
  )
  :caveats ("a and b should both be non-negative; negative values produce undefined behavior." "If a or b is zero, the ratio is degenerate; visualizations may not render sensibly." "This returns a spec, not a rendered image; a separate verb must visualize." "Large values of a and b may be visually difficult to represent as discrete units.")
  :drawbacks ("Spec-only: requires a visualization pipeline to display the actual bar." "Not suitable for exact symbolic ratio manipulation (use for pedagogy/visualization)." "If a and b are very large, rendering may be slow or cluttered.")
  :usecases ("Teaching students to understand ratios and proportions visually." "Building interactive ratio and proportion problem solvers." "Illustrating equivalent ratios and scaling." "Creating visual aids for word problems involving mixtures, recipes, and rates.")
  :related ("math/fraction-bar" "math/number-line" "math/compare" "math/count-on" "math/area-model")
  :learn (:concept "Ratio bar: visual model showing the multiplicative relationship a:b between two quantities." :prerequisites ("math/fraction-bar") :progression "After math/ratio-bar, explore math/fraction-bar for parts of a whole, then solve/proportion for ratio equations.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A recipe-scaling lesson shows a 2:3 water-to-flour ratio." :program "(define spec (math/ratio-bar 2 3))
spec" :explanation "Emit the spec that renders as a bar in the 2:3 proportion." :meta "math/ratio-bar is the correct verb because it names the ratio pedagogy. fraction-bar shows part-of-whole; ratio-bar shows part-to-part.")
    (:eng "Log the operator's stated problem and the code path chosen; audits catch cases where a sibling verb would silently succeed with wrong answers." :math "The audit lens fixes the mathematical function class (unary, binary, inverse, aggregate) and gates on argument-domain checks stated in the caveats." :cs "Row 2 emphasizes single-call, single-effect: pure functions may be replaced by their memoized result; audits check that no impure sibling was substituted."))
